<TITLE> UK Feb global trade gap narrows in line with forecasts </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's goods trade deficit with the rest of the world in February narrowed in line with forecasts to its smallest since August 2007 as oil exports rose and overall imports fell, official data showed on Thursday. The Office for National Statistics said that Britain's goods trade gap narrowed to 7.487 billion pounds in February from 7.924 billion in January. Economists had forecast a deficit of 7.5 billion pounds. The goods trade gap with non-EU countries narrowed to 4.023 billion pounds from 4.274 billion -- also the smallest since August 2007 and confounding analyst forecasts for a deficit of 4.30 billion pounds. The figures are unlikely to alter expectations for a Bank of England interest rate cut later on Thursday, but may reflect a weakness in the pound making imports more expensive and boosting overseas demand for British oil. Exports to non-EU countries hit a record high, up to 8.636 billion pounds from 8.193 billion pounds. The oil balance moved into surplus for the first time since mid-2007 to hit its highest since April 2006 at 82 million pounds, up from a deficit of 482 million pounds in January. However, policymakers may be concerned to see import price inflation picking up over the previous three months, with the three-month on three-month reading rising to 3.2 percent from 2.2 percent in January, which the ONS said was the highest since the mid-199
